      {
        "position": 7,
        "title": "Good quality, fits and works well!",
        "text": "I have a dog who recently decided that she hates a LONG list of noises, with thunder being at the top of the list...Unfortunately, for at least three months a year, we have frequent thunderstorms in our area. I started experimenting with compression vests like this one during our last thunderstorm season, and found that the compression helped her quite a lot. This is the second short of this type that I've tried, and there are a number of factors that make it better than the first one I tried:The fabric is soft and stretchy, and it fits her well--to have the desired effect, it needs to be snug, and I can wrap this to fit her tightly while it's stretchy enough for her to move comfortably.My wondermutt is 70 pounds with a deep chest and a narrow waist (she's what happens when a string-mop of an Old English sheepdog sweeps a poodle off her paws...She's a glorious mutt!) The XL fits her perfectly.The shirt definitely calms her, and I think it's helped that we've conditioned her to know that good things (and snacks!) happen when we get out the shirt. While training is not strictly necessary, giving her positive associations with the shirt means that she doesn't object to me putting it on.The design makes it easy to put on--I secure the neck band first, then burrito wrap her with the waist bands. The whole process takes maybe 30 seconds.The quality is good--the one I received was cleanly finished and there are no scratchy bits of velcro or loose ends or crooked seams.This is definitely a product I'd recommend, and the price is definitely on par for the product.(Pardon the sad face in the photos...That has nothing to do with wearing the shirt and everything to do with the expectation of a treat that has yet to arrive even though the shirt has come out...)",
